docs.abstract: Lawsuits filed Tuesday and Wednesday accused the Houston Texans quarterback of misconduct during massages last year. Watson said in a statement Tuesday that he had never “treated any woman with anything other than the utmost respect.”
docs.snippet: Lawsuits filed Tuesday and Wednesday accused the Houston Texans quarterback of misconduct during massages last year. Watson said in a statement Tuesday that he had never “treated any woman with anything other than the utmost respect.”
docs.lead_paragraph: Deshaun Watson, the star quarterback of the Houston Texans, has been accused of sexually assaulting three massage therapists last year in three separate civil suits filed this week in Harris County, Texas.

headline.main: Deshaun Watson Accused of Sexual Assault in Civil Suits
headline.print_headline: In 2 Civil Suits, Houston’s Quarterback Is Accused of Sexual Assault

byline.original: By Ken Belson and Ben Shpigel

docs.abstract: Can you be both an agent of change and art-world royalty? This artist’s reign on the Whitney Museum’s fifth floor shows it’s possible.
docs.snippet: Can you be both an agent of change and art-world royalty? This artist’s reign on the Whitney Museum’s fifth floor shows it’s possible.
docs.lead_paragraph: In a moment when museum collections are trying to integrate more women and artists of color, Julie Mehretu represents a powerful symbol of progress, the rare example of a contemporary Black female painter who has already entered the canon.

docs.abstract: The first three jurors were selected on Tuesday, with one saying he was not “scared to take on a trial of this magnitude.”
docs.snippet: The first three jurors were selected on Tuesday, with one saying he was not “scared to take on a trial of this magnitude.”
docs.lead_paragraph: The first three jurors were selected on Tuesday for the trial of Derek Chauvin, the former Minneapolis police officer accused of second-degree murder in the death of George Floyd.

headline.main: What happened on the first day of jury selection at the Derek Chauvin trial?

docs.abstract: In Britain and beyond, protesters on the left and right are rebelling against virus restrictions, drawing harsh police responses — and questions about the officers’ legitimacy.
docs.snippet: In Britain and beyond, protesters on the left and right are rebelling against virus restrictions, drawing harsh police responses — and questions about the officers’ legitimacy.
docs.lead_paragraph: LONDON — In Bristol, an English college town where the pubs are usually packed with students, there were fiery clashes between the police and protesters. In Kassel, a German city known for its ambitious contemporary art festival, the police unleashed pepper spray and water cannons on anti-lockdown marchers.

headline.main: As Europe’s Lockdowns Drag On, Police and Protesters Clash
headline.print_headline: Europe’s Lockdown Rebellions Meet Batons and Pepper Spray

byline.original: By Mark Landler and Stephen Castle

docs.abstract: Videos echoing the death of George Floyd showed a police officer kneeling on the back of the woman, who died of a broken spine, just days before an international forum on gender equality began in Mexico.
docs.snippet: Videos echoing the death of George Floyd showed a police officer kneeling on the back of the woman, who died of a broken spine, just days before an international forum on gender equality began in Mexico.
docs.lead_paragraph: MEXICO CITY — The death at the hands of police of a woman who was a refugee from El Salvador has drawn international condemnation and potential embarrassment for Mexico, which on Monday began hosting a United Nations summit focused on gender equality.

headline.main: Killing of Salvadoran Refugee by Police in Mexico Incites Furor
headline.print_headline: Mexico Police  Face Scrutiny After Woman Dies in Tulum

docs.abstract: The hiring of Alexi McCammond, who was supposed to start at the Condé Nast publication next week, drew complaints because of racist and homophobic tweets she had posted a decade ago.
docs.snippet: The hiring of Alexi McCammond, who was supposed to start at the Condé Nast publication next week, drew complaints because of racist and homophobic tweets she had posted a decade ago.
docs.lead_paragraph: Alexi McCammond, who made her name as a politics reporter at the Washington news site Axios, had planned to start as the editor in chief of Teen Vogue next Wednesday. Now, after Teen Vogue staff members publicly condemned racist and homophobic tweets Ms. McCammond had posted a decade ago, she has resigned from the job.

headline.main: Teen Vogue Editor Resigns After Fury Over Racist Tweets
headline.print_headline: Newly Hired Editor of Teen Vogue Resigns Over Racist Tweets

docs.abstract: “I’m not sure Asian-American families can avoid ‘the talk’ any longer,” one expert said.
docs.snippet: “I’m not sure Asian-American families can avoid ‘the talk’ any longer,” one expert said.
docs.lead_paragraph: My daughter was the only kid who didn’t have a separate Korean name when we signed her up for Korean classes three years ago. The blank space on the registration form looked at me, as if to say we’d forgotten something as parents.

headline.main: I’m Helping My Korean-American Daughter Embrace Her Identity to Counter Racism

docs.abstract: A nurse struggles with low morale; a waiter worries about a rush to normalcy; a respiratory therapist recovers from Covid, and more.
docs.snippet: A nurse struggles with low morale; a waiter worries about a rush to normalcy; a respiratory therapist recovers from Covid, and more.
docs.lead_paragraph: Last March the Sunday Routine column, which typically profiles New Yorkers enjoying the city on their day off, switched gears to profile essential workers.

headline.main: How Essential Workers Who Shared Their Sundays With Us Are Doing, One Year In
headline.print_headline: Catching Up With New Yorkers Who Are Still in the Thick of It

byline.original: By Alix Strauss and Hilary Howard

docs.abstract: Several politically charged investigations await Judge Merrick B. Garland, President Biden’s nominee for attorney general.
docs.snippet: Several politically charged investigations await Judge Merrick B. Garland, President Biden’s nominee for attorney general.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — As Judge Merrick B. Garland prepares to take over the Justice Department, officials have already begun to reverse Trump-era policies denounced by Democrats and restore what longtime employees described as a less charged environment where they no longer feared retaliation from the president or public criticism from the attorney general.

headline.main: Justice Dept. Backs Away From Trump Era but Is Still Expected to Test Garland
headline.print_headline: Justice Dept. Retreats From Trump Era but Is Still Likely to Test Garland
